<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much overage do I need for quilt backing?", answer: "For longarm quilting, add 4 inches of overage on each side of the quilt top — so 8 inches total to both width and length. This extra fabric is clamped into the longarm frame and is absolutely necessary; skimping on it will frustrate your longarm quilter. For home machine quilting or hand quilting, you can get away with 2 to 3 inches of overage per side, which is about 4 to 6 inches total to each dimension." },
  { question: "What is wide-back quilt fabric?", answer: "Wide-back fabric is quilting cotton sold in 108-inch widths specifically for quilt backing. It eliminates the need to piece the backing for most bed-sized quilts, saving time and avoiding the bulky seam down the middle. Wide-back prints are usually tonal or subtle so they don't compete with the quilt top. They cost more per yard than standard 42-inch fabric but save yardage overall because you don't need multiple pieced panels." },
  { question: "Should my backing have a horizontal or vertical seam?", answer: "The choice depends on your quilt dimensions — pick the orientation that uses less total yardage. Generally, if your quilt is longer than it is wide, a vertical seam (panels running lengthwise) uses less fabric. If your quilt is wider than it is long, a horizontal seam is more efficient. This calculator automatically picks the orientation with the lower yardage. Some quilters prefer one orientation regardless of yardage to avoid a seam at the visual center." },
  { question: "Do I need to pre-wash backing fabric?", answer: "Pre-washing backing fabric is a personal choice. Some quilters pre-wash everything to remove sizing, eliminate shrinkage, and test colorfastness, especially for reds and deep blues that are prone to bleeding. Others prefer the crispness of unwashed fabric and accept some shrinkage when the finished quilt is washed. If you pre-wash the backing, also pre-wash the top and batting to avoid differential shrinkage creating wrinkles." },
  { question: "Can I piece backing from multiple fabrics?", answer: "Absolutely — pieced backings are a great way to use up large leftover pieces and reduce fabric costs. Aim for a few large sections rather than tiny scraps, and avoid bulky seams at the edges where the longarm frame attaches. Pressed seams should lie flat, and any directional prints should be oriented consistently. A pieced backing is sometimes called a scrappy backing and can become a design feature of the finished quilt." }
]) %>

